          "body": "2 Kings 10 cannot be read apart from the prophetic commissions that precede it. At Horeb, God told Elijah to anoint Jehu king over Israel (1 Kings 19:16-17). Elisha's servant completed the anointing in 2 Kings 9:1-10, charging Jehu to 'strike the house of Ahab your master, that I may avenge the blood of My servants the prophets' (9:7). Chapter 10 is the execution of that mandate. The narrator frames every scene of carnage through prophetic fulfillment language: 'Know then that there shall fall to the earth nothing of the word of the LORD which He spoke concerning the house of Ahab' (10:10); 'he destroyed him, according to the word of the LORD which He spoke to Elijah' (10:17). Jehu is not an autonomous revolutionary — he is a historical actor working within a divinely scripted prophetic arc. The reader must interpret the violence through that framework, not through the categories of modern political ethics or ancient Near Eastern power politics alone."
