          "body": "Verse 29 is the theological center of the chapter's assessment. The single Hebrew adversative *raq* ('however, only, but') immediately qualifies the triumph of verse 28. Jehu did not depart from the golden calves of Jeroboam at Bethel and Dan — the alternative worship centers established by Israel's first northern king to prevent his subjects from returning to Jerusalem (1 Kings 12:25-33). Those calves served Jehu's political interests: they maintained northern religious identity against Jerusalem's pull, and they gave his dynasty an independent cultic system. To have destroyed them would have been politically costly. Jehu was willing to destroy Baal — an imported Phoenician cult with Omride associations — but not to dismantle the domestic religious infrastructure that served his own power. The pattern is recognizable in every generation: the idols we eradicate are those that threaten us; the idols we retain are those that serve us. Verse 31 presses deeper — Jehu did not walk in the Torah 'with all his heart' (*bekhol-levavo*). The whole-heart standard is the Deuteronomic criterion (Deuteronomy 6:5; 1 Kings 8:61), and Jehu failed it. The territorial loss to Hazael (10:32-33) is the immediate divine consequence — not after his death, but within his reign."
