        "body": "The opening seventeen verses document the complete elimination of the Omride political network in both its northern seat (Jezreel) and its capital (Samaria). Jehu's method is strategic rather than straightforwardly military: he tests the Samarian leadership's loyalty with an ironic challenge to fight for Ahab's house (10:2-3), receives their capitulation (10:5), and then commands them to become instruments of the purge they could have resisted (10:6-7). The test-and-command sequence makes the ruling class complicit, eliminating both the princes and the possibility of organized resistance in a single stroke.\n\nThe public speech at the gate (10:9-10) is the narrator's theological commentary placed on Jehu's own lips. 'I conspired against my master and killed him, but who killed all these?' The question is rhetorical — the crowd cannot answer it, and Jehu supplies God as the answer (10:10). The seventy heads are thus framed as divine action through distributed human agency. The narrator endorses this interpretation by repeating the prophetic-fulfillment formula in his own voice at 10:17. The formula 'according to the word of the LORD which He spoke to Elijah' brackets the dynastic purge, occurring in Jehu's speech (10:10) and the narrator's summary (10:17) to create a theological envelope around the entire unit.\n\nThe killing of Ahaziah's relatives (10:13-14) raises a distinct question. These forty-two men were not members of Ahab's northern dynasty; they were Judahite princes visiting their Omride kin (Ahaziah's mother was Athaliah, an Omride princess — 2 Kings 8:26). Jehu's expansion of the purge to include them is not explicitly sanctioned by the Elijah prophecy, and the narrator offers no direct commendation or condemnation. The episode demonstrates that Jehu's purge acquired a momentum beyond its original prophetic scope — a pattern that Hosea 1:4 will later address when the prophet declares that the LORD will punish the house of Jehu 'for the bloodshed of Jezreel,' suggesting that not all of Jehu's violence was within the covenant commission.\n\nThe Jehonadab episode (10:15-16) is the chapter's most revealing character moment. Jehonadab son of Rechab was the founder of the Rechabite community — ascetic Yahwists who drank no wine, built no houses, and planted no vineyards (Jeremiah 35:6-10). His reputation as a zealous Yahwist was unassailable. Jehu's invitation — 'Is your heart right, as my heart is with your heart?' — uses the heart-language that will return in 10:30-31. Jehonadab's assent and his visible presence in Jehu's chariot lend the purge an air of prophetic legitimacy. But the narrator's later verdict (10:31) that Jehu did not walk with 'all his heart' implicitly contrasts him with the Rechabite whose whole-hearted devotion was his defining characteristic.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Davar* (word) appears three times in v. 10 — as noun, verbal root in 'spoke,' and verbal root in 'promised' — emphasizing the reliability of prophetic speech. *Yada* (know) in Jehu's command is the same root used for experiential, covenantal knowledge throughout the Old Testament; Jehu is not asking the crowd for intellectual assent but for recognition of divine action."
