        "excerpt": "But Jehu did it in cunning, so that he might destroy the worshipers of Baal.",
        "body": "The Baal-temple pericope (10:18-28) is the chapter's most extended narrative unit and its most morally complex. The narrator front-loads his editorial comment in verse 19: Jehu's public declaration of devotion to Baal was deliberate deception (*oqvah*, 'cunning,' 'guile'). This disclosure prevents the reader from being confused by Jehu's apparent Baal-piety and frames what follows as a sustained strategic deception in service of a genuine Yahwist objective.\n\nThe operation has multiple layers of meticulous planning. First, a kingdom-wide summons ensures maximum attendance (10:20-21) — the narrator notes that 'the house of Baal was filled from one end to the other,' indicating the cult's extensive reach even after Elijah's contest on Carmel. Second, identifying garments are issued to mark every worshiper (10:22), ensuring no one can later claim they were not present. Third, the search for Yahweh's servants (10:23) is Jehu's own protection clause — no Yahwist is to be killed in the action, suggesting Jehu understood the limits of divinely sanctioned violence. Fourth, eighty soldiers are pre-positioned outside (10:24) with lethal accountability attached to any escape. Fifth, the massacre is timed to the completion of the burnt offering — the moment of maximum religious absorption, when escape is least expected.\n\nThe destruction of the sacred pillars (*matstsevot*), the demolition of the house, and its conversion to a latrine (10:26-27) represent a systematic desecration that went beyond killing the worshipers to dismantling the cultic infrastructure. A *matstsevah* (sacred standing stone) was the material anchor of Baalist worship; burning and breaking it severed the cultic site's sacred identity. Converting the building to a latrine (*macharaah*, an outhouse or privy) is the narrator's driest irony — the holiest site in Baal's national cult became the most ritually impure location in Israelite categorization.\n\nThe summary verdict of verse 28 — 'Thus Jehu eradicated Baal out of Israel' — is the chapter's most positive statement and historically accurate. Archaeological evidence from Samaria shows a discontinuity in Baalist cult objects after the Omride period. The Baal temples do not re-appear in the northern kingdom's subsequent history in Kings. Whatever the means, Jehu's purge was historically effective. The narrator acknowledges this unreservedly before the devastating turn of verse 29.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Oqvah* (cunning, guile) is rare in biblical Hebrew; it carries the sense of deliberate strategic deception. *Matstsevah* (sacred pillar) was a standing stone used in both legitimate Yahweh worship at patriarchal sites (Genesis 28:18) and in Canaanite Baal religion — by the monarchic period the term was almost exclusively associated with idolatrous practice. *Macharaah* (latrine) is a unique term in the Hebrew Bible, used only here; the specificity suggests an actual, well-known desecration visible to the narrator's audience."
