        "excerpt": "However, as for the sins of Jeroboam the son of Nebat, which he made Israel sin, from these Jehu did not depart, even the golden calves that were at Bethel and that were at Dan.",
        "body": "Verse 29 opens with *raq* — 'however,' 'only,' 'but.' In Hebrew narrative, *raq* following a positive summary statement is the narrator's most economical way of introducing a qualification that overturns the dominant impression. The sequence is intentional: the triumph of verse 28 ('eradicated Baal') is immediately followed by the concession of verse 29 ('did not depart from the sins of Jeroboam'). The literary structure enacts the theological reality: Jehu's achievement, though genuine, was incomplete in a way that mattered decisively to God.\n\nThe 'sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat' is the Kings narrator's fixed formula for the golden-calf worship established by Jeroboam I at Bethel and Dan (1 Kings 12:28-30). When Jeroboam said 'Here are your gods, O Israel, who brought you up from the land of Egypt,' he was recycling the language of the golden-calf apostasy at Sinai (Exodus 32:4) in a politically motivated alternative cultic system designed to prevent his subjects from traveling to Jerusalem. The phrase 'which he made Israel sin' (*asher hecheti et Yisrael*) is causal — Jeroboam's sin was not merely personal but causative, dragging the entire northern population into covenant violation. Jehu inherits this sin-structure and leaves it untouched.\n\nWhy does Jehu retain the golden calves while eradicating Baal? The most persuasive historical answer is political calculus. Baal worship was associated with the Omride dynasty and its Phoenician alliances — eliminating it was both prophetically required and politically advantageous for the new regime. The golden calves at Bethel and Dan, by contrast, were the indigenous northern religious establishment, deeply woven into the identity of the kingdom's population and essential for maintaining northern independence from Jerusalem. To destroy them would have been to hand cultic authority back to the Davidic temple — an unacceptable concession for a northern king whose legitimacy did not rest on the Davidic covenant.\n\nVerse 31 presses the diagnosis to its root: Jehu was not careful (*shamar*, to guard, watch carefully) to walk in the Torah of the LORD 'with all his heart' (*bekhol-levavo*). The whole-heart formula is the Deuteronomic standard — Deuteronomy 6:5 requires loving the LORD 'with all your heart, with all your soul, and with all your might.' The same criterion evaluates every Israelite king in the Kings framework. Jehu executed God's commission; he did not love God with whole-hearted devotion. The distinction is critical for students of this text: obedience to specific divine mandates is not the same as covenant faithfulness of the heart. God receives Jehu's acts; He also names what the acts lacked.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Raq* (only, however) is a limiting particle — it does not negate what precedes but radically qualifies it. *Shamar* (to be careful, to guard) implies deliberate, watchful diligence — its absence means not negligence but willful non-compliance. *Bekhol-levavo* (with all his heart) — the whole-heart idiom occurs in Deuteronomy 6:5; 1 Kings 8:61; 11:4; 14:8; 15:3, 14; always as the standard against which kings are measured."
