        "body": "The theological precision of verses 30-33 is among the most sophisticated passages in the Kings history. God addresses Jehu directly (10:30) — one of the few occasions in Kings when God speaks to a northern king — and the divine speech is unambiguously positive: 'you have done well,' 'you have done according to all that was in My heart.' The *because* (*ya'an asher*) construction makes the reward causally dependent on specific obedience. God's promise of four generations on the throne (confirmed in 2 Kings 15:12 with Zechariah) is kept precisely because the prophetic mandate was executed. God does not pretend Jehu's obedience was absent when it was present.\n\nYet the very next verse (10:31) returns to the narrator's censure: 'Yet Jehu was not careful to walk in the law of the LORD, the God of Israel, with all his heart.' The juxtaposition is deliberate and must not be harmonized away. God commends what was genuinely commendable and indicts what was genuinely deficient. This is not double-mindedness in God; it is the precision of covenantal assessment. Douglas Moo's commentary principle applies here analogically: the sacred author holds multiple true things together that the reader's categorizing instinct wants to separate. Reformed interpreters in the tradition of Calvin have noted this passage as evidence that God may use an instrument for His purposes who is not personally godly — a truth both comforting and sobering.\n\nVerse 32 introduces the temporal marker 'in those days' — within Jehu's own reign, not after it, the LORD 'began to cut off portions from Israel' (*chalal liqtson*). The verb *chalal* (to begin, to start) is the narrator's signal that what follows is the commencement of a process, not a single event. Hazael of Damascus defeats Israel throughout its territory, seizing the entire Transjordanian region — Gilead, Bashan, and the tribal territories of Gad, Reuben, and Manasseh (10:33). This is not presented as Hazael's military achievement but as God's action: 'the LORD began to cut off.' The same sovereign God who empowered Jehu to eradicate Baal is now empowering Hazael to dismember Israel, because the internal covenant failure (retained golden calves, divided heart) carries external territorial consequences.\n\nThe historical background sharpens the interpretation. The Assyrian Black Obelisk of Shalmaneser III depicts 'Iaua son of Humri' (almost certainly Jehu or his representative) prostrating before the Assyrian king and paying tribute — dated to approximately 841 BC, the early years of Jehu's reign. Jehu's kingdom was under both Assyrian pressure from the northeast and Aramean/Damascene pressure from the north. The loss of Transjordan to Hazael is confirmed by Amos 1:3-5 and the Aramean expansion known from 2 Kings 12-13. The narrator is not writing theological fiction; he is interpreting real political and military events through the lens of covenant faithfulness.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ya'an asher* (because) — causal construction tying the dynastic promise explicitly to Jehu's specific obedience. *Chalal* (began) — the Piel form of the verb denotes commencement of an action, here the deliberate initiation of territorial reduction as divine discipline. *Qatsah* (to cut off) — to reduce, diminish, cut down the edges; the territorial image is of God pruning the borders of His people because of covenant violation."
