        "excerpt": "And Jehu slept with his fathers, and they buried him in Samaria. And Jehoahaz his son became king in his place. Now the time which Jehu reigned over Israel in Samaria was twenty-eight years.",
        "body": "The regnal summary formula (10:34-36) is the Kings narrator's standard closing for every king, but its brevity here is itself a theological statement. The formula — 'Now the rest of the acts of Jehu and all that he did and all his might, are they not written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?' — acknowledges that the chapter has not exhausted Jehu's story; political and military records exist elsewhere. But the Kings narrator is not writing political history. He is writing theological history, and the two facts that matter for his purposes have already been stated: God commended Jehu's obedience (10:30) and God held Jehu's deficiency accountable (10:31-32).\n\nTwenty-eight years is the longest reign in the Jehu dynasty and, notably, the longest reign of any northern king in the book of Kings to this point. Yet the summary is stark. There is no additional positive verdict ('he did right in the eyes of the LORD') as appears for southern kings like Asa (1 Kings 15:11) or Hezekiah (2 Kings 18:3). There is no reformer's legacy statement. Jehu's burial in Samaria — the city he conquered and the city where he chose to be buried — is the final irony: the man who eradicated Baal in Samaria (10:28) rests in Samaria, leaving a kingdom already losing its eastern borders.\n\nThe succession to Jehoahaz marks the beginning of the dynasty's continuation — the four-generation promise of 10:30 will play out across 2 Kings 13-15 through Jehoahaz, Joash, Jeroboam II, and Zechariah. Each successor inherits the same structural sin: none departs from the sins of Jeroboam. The Jehu dynasty is thus a monument to both divine faithfulness (God keeps His word about four generations) and divine patience (He endures the golden calves through four more reigns before the Assyrian destruction ends the northern kingdom in 722 BC). The chapter's closing verse, stripped of elaboration, leaves Jehu exactly where the narrator has placed him throughout: a man whom God used greatly, assessed honestly, rewarded partially, and judged truly."
